member.name: T:GF.CommLib.Maybe`1
member.summary:
An instance of Maybe contains either a particular value, or None. It is a superior alternative to encoding meaning in null references.
This pattern is best used with the convention that null references are always in error, except for when they are unavoidable (e.g. used by a third party library). If null references are considered meaningful, then every instance reference encodes two values: both the value itself and the presence or absence of the value. Therefore, every instance reference is suspect and should be checked against null. But most instance references are intended to always have a value, and null checking is noisy and verbose, so null is only sometimes checked.
Most null reference exceptions are caused by this ambiguity. The Maybe pattern eliminates this entire class of run-time errors.
